=New+York&amp;rft.pages=vii-xi%2C+3-26&amp;rft.pub=Routledge&amp;rft.date=2013&amp;rft.isbn=978-0-7146-3142-4&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AMuhammad" class="Z3988" about="#mwt1916" id="mwCcE"></span><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r879151008" about="#mwt1916" typeof="mw:Extension/templatestyles" data-mw='{"name":"templatestyles","attrs":{"src":"Module:Citation/CS1/styles.css"},"body":{"extsrc":""}}' id="mwCcI"/>; <cite class="citation book" about="#mwt1917" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"cite book ","href":"./Template:Cite_book"},"params":{"editor1-last":{"wt":"Willis"},"editor1-first":{"wt":"John Ralph"},"date":{"wt":"1985"},"title":{"wt":"Slaves and Slavery in Muslim Africa: The Servile Estate"},"location":{"wt":"[[New York City|New York]]"},"publisher":{"wt":"[[Routledge Press|Routledge]]"},"volume":{"wt":"2"},"pp":{"wt":"vii-xi"},"isbn":{"wt":"978-0-7146-3201-8"}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwCcM">Willis, John Ralph, ed. (1985). <i id="mwCcQ">Slaves and Slavery in Muslim Africa: The Servile Estate</i>. <b id="mwCcU">2</b>. <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./New_York_City" title="New York City" id="mwCcY">New York</a>: <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Routledge_Press" title="Routledge Press" id="mwCcc" class="mw-redirect">Routledge</a>. pp.<span typeof="mw:Entity" id="mwCcg"> </span>vii–xi. <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./International_Standard_Book_Number" title="International Standard Book Number" id="mwCck">ISBN</a><span typeof="mw:Entity" id="mwCco"> </span><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Special:BookSources/978-0-7146-3201-8" title="Special:BookSources/978-0-7146-3201-8" id="mwCcs">978-0-7146-3201-8</a>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Slaves+and+Slavery+in+Muslim+Africa%3A+The+Servile+Estate&amp;rft.place=New+York&amp;rft.pages=vii-xi&amp;rft.pub=Routledge&amp;rft.date=1985&amp;rft.isbn=978-0-7146-3201-8&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AMuhammad" class="Z3988" about="#mwt1917" id="mwCcw"></span><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r879151008" about="#mwt1917" typeof="mw:Extension/templatestyles" data-mw='{"name":"templatestyles","attrs":{"src":"Module:Citation/CS1/styles.css"},"body":{"extsrc":""}}' id="mwCc0"/></span></li><li about="#cite_note-329" id="cite_note-329"><a href="./Muhammad#cite_ref-329" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-329" class="mw-reference-text">See also <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./History_of_slavery_in_the_Muslim_world" title="History of slavery in the Muslim world" id="mwCc4">History of slavery in the Muslim world</a>, <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Arab_slave_trade" title="Arab slave trade" id="mwCc8">Arab slave trade</a>, <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Slavery_in_the_Ottoman_Empire" title="Slavery in the Ottoman Empire" id="mwCdA">Slavery in the Ottoman Empire</a>, and <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Slavery_in_21st-century_Islamism" title="Slavery in 21st-century Islamism" id="mwCdE">Slavery in 21st-century Islamism</a>.</span></li><li about="#cite_note-JE1-330" id="cite_note-JE1-330"><span rel="mw:referencedBy"><a href="./Muhammad#cite_ref-JE1_330-0"><span class="mw-linkback-text">1 </span></a><a href="./Muhammad#cite_ref-JE1_330-1"><span class="mw-linkback-text">2 </span></a><a href="./Muhammad#cite_ref-JE1_330-2"><span class="mw-linkback-text">3 </span></a><a href="./Muhammad#cite_ref-JE1_330-3"><span class="mw-linkback-text">4 </span></a></span> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-JE1-330" class="mw-reference-text"><span about="#mwt1918" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"Cquote","href":"./Template:Cquote"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"During the twenty-five years of his union with [[Khadija bint Khuwaylid|Ḥadijah]] Mohammed had no other wife; but scarcely two months had elapsed after her death (619) when he married Sauda, the widow of Sakran, who, with her husband, had become an early convert to Islam and who was one of the emigrants to Abyssinia. At about the same time Mohammed contracted an engagement with [[Aisha|&apos;A&apos;ishah]], the six-year-old daughter of [[Abu Bakr]], and married her shortly after his arrival at Medina. &apos;A&apos;ishah was the only one of his wives who had not been previously married; and she remained his favorite to the end. [...] In his married life, as well as in his religious life, a change seems to have come over Mohammed after his removal to Medina. In the space of ten years he took twelve or thirteen wives and had several concubines: even the faithful were scandalized, and the prophet had to resort to alleged special revelations from God to justify his conduct. Such was the case when he wished to marry [[Zaynab bint Jahsh|Zainab]], the wife of his adopted son [[Zayd ibn Harithah|Zaid]]."},"author":{"wt":"Richard Gottheil, Mary W. Montgomery, Hubert Grimme"},"source":{"wt":"[http://jewishencyclopedia.com/articles/10918-mohammed \"Mohammed\"] (1906), &apos;&apos;[[Jewish Encyclopedia]]&apos;&apos;, [[Kopelman Foundation]]."}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwCdI">
</span><link rel="mw:PageProp/Category" href="./Category:Articles_with_attributed_pull_quotes" about="#mwt1918" id="mwCdM"/><table class="cquote pullquote" role="presentation" style="margin:auto; border-collapse: collapse; border: none; background-color: transparent; width: auto; " about="#mwt1918" id="mwCdQ">
<tbody id="mwCdU"><tr id="mwCdY"><td style="width: 20px; vertical-align: top; border: none; color: #B2B7F2; font-size: 40px; font-family: 'Times New Roman', Times, serif; font-weight: bold; line-height: .6em; text-align: left; padding: 10px 10px;" id="mwCdc">“</td>
<td style="vertical-align: top; border: none; padding: 4px 10px; " id="mwCdg">During the twenty-five years of his union with <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Khadija_bint_Khuwaylid" title="Khadija bint Khuwaylid" id="mwCdk">Ḥadijah</a> Mohammed had no other wife; but scarcely two months had elapsed after her death (619) when he married Sauda, the widow of Sakran, who, with her husband, had become an early convert to Islam and who was one of the emigrants to Abyssinia. At about the same time Mohammed contracted an engagement with <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Aisha" title="Aisha" id="mwCdo">'A'ishah</a>, the six-year-old daughter of <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Abu_Bakr" title="Abu Bakr" id="mwCds">Abu Bakr</a>, and married her shortly after his arrival at Medina. 'A'ishah was the only one of his wives who had not been previously married; and she remained his favorite to the end. [...] In his married life, as well as in his religious life, a change seems to have come over Mohammed after his removal to Medina. In the space of ten years he took twelve or thirteen wives and had several concubines: even the faithful were scandalized, and the prophet had to resort to alleged special revelations from God to justify his conduct. Such was the case when he wished to marry <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Zaynab_bint_Jahsh" title="Zaynab bint Jahsh" id="mwCdw">Zainab</a>, the wife of his adopted son <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Zayd_ibn_Harithah" title="Zayd ibn Harithah" id="mwCd0">Zaid</a>.</td>
<td style="width: 20px; vertical-align: bottom; border: none; color: #B2B7F2; font-size: 40px; font-family: 'Times New Roman', Times, serif; font-weight: bold; line-height: .6em; text-align: right; padding: 10px 10px;" id="mwCd4">”</td></tr>
<tr id="mwCd8">

<td colspan="3" class="cquotecite" style="border: none; padding-right: 4%; font-size: smaller; line-height:normal; text-align: right;" id="mwCeA"><cite id="mwCeE">—<span typeof="mw:Entity" id="mwCeI"> </span>Richard Gottheil, Mary W. Montgomery, Hubert Grimme, <a rel="mw:ExtLink" class="external text" href="http://jewishencyclopedia.com/articles/10918-mohammed" id="mwCeM">"Mohammed"</a> (1906), <i id="mwCeQ"><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Jewish_Encyclopedia" title="Jewish Encyclopedia" id="mwCeU" class="mw-redirect">Jewish Encyclopedia</a></i>, <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Kopelman_Foundation" title="Kopelman Foundation" id="mwCeY" class="mw-redirect">Kopelman Foundation</a>.</cite></td></tr>
</tbody></table></span></li><li about="#cite_note-331" id="cite_note-331"><a href="./Muhammad#cite_ref-331" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-331" class="mw-reference-text"><span about="#mwt1919" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"Cquote","href":"./Template:Cquote"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"The messenger of God went out into the marketplace of Medina and had trenches dug in it; then he sent for them and had them beheaded in those trenches. They were brought out to him in groups. Among them were the enemy of God, Huyayy b. Akhtab, and Ka’b b. Asad, the head of the tribe. They numbered 600 or 700—the largest estimate says they were between 800 and 900. As they were being taken in groups to the Messenger of God, they said to Ka’b b. Asad, \"Ka’b, what do you understand. Do you not see that the summoner does not discharge [anyone] and that those of you who are taken away do not come back? By God, it is death!\" the affair continued until the Messenger of God had finished with them."},"author":{"wt":"[[Al-Tabari]]"},"source":{"wt":"[https://books.google.com/books?id=-ppPqzawIrIC&amp;pg=PA201 &apos;&apos;Victory of Islam, Volume 8&apos;&apos;], translated by Michael Fishbein (1997), State University of New York Press, pp. 35–36, {{ISBN|978-0-7914-3150-4}}."}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwCec">
</span><link rel="mw:PageProp/Category" href="./Category:Articles_with_attributed_pull_quotes" about="#mwt1919" id="mwCeg"/><table class="cquote pullquote" role="presentation" style="margin:auto; border-collapse: collapse; border: none; background-color: transparent; width: auto; " about="#mwt1919" id="mwCek">
<tbody id="mwCeo"><tr id="mwCes"><td style="width: 20px; vertical-align: top; border: none; color: #B2B7F2; font-size: 40px; font-family: 'Times New Roman', Times, serif; font-weight: bold; line-height: .6em; text-align: left; padding: 10px 10px;" id="mwCew">“</td>
<td style="vertical-align: top; border: none; padding: 4px 10px; " id="mwCe0">The messenger of God went out into the marketplace of Medina and had trenches dug in it; then he sent for them and had them beheaded in those trenches. They were brought out to him in groups. Among them were the enemy of God, Huyayy b. Akhtab, and Ka’b b. Asad, the head of the tribe. They numbered 600 or 700—the largest estimate says they were between 800 and 900. As they were being taken in groups to the Messenger of God, they said to Ka’b b. Asad, "Ka’b, what do you understand. Do you not see that the summoner does not discharge [anyone] and that those of you who are taken away do not come back? By God, it is death!" the affair continued until the Messenger of God had finished with them.</td>
<td style="width: 20px; vertical-align: bottom; border: none; color: #B2B7F2; font-size: 40px; font-family: 'Times New Roman', Times, serif; font-weight: bold; line-height: .6em; text-align: right; padding: 10px 10px;" id="mwCe4">”</td></tr>
<tr id="mwCe8">

<td colspan="3" class="cquotecite" style="border: none; padding-right: 4%; font-size: smaller; line-height:normal; text-align: right;" id="mwCfA"><cite id="mwCfE">—<span typeof="mw:Entity" id="mwCfI"> </span><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Al-Tabari" title="Al-Tabari" id="mwCfM">Al-Tabari</a>, <a rel="mw:ExtLink" class="external text" href="https://books.google.com/books?id=-ppPqzawIrIC&amp;pg=PA201" id="mwCfQ"><i id="mwCfU">Victory of Islam, Volume 8</i></a>, translated by Michael Fishbein (1997), State University of New York Press, pp. 35–36, <link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r879151008" about="#mwt2511" typeof="mw:Extension/templatestyles" data-mw='{"name":"templatestyles","attrs":{"src":"Module:Citation/CS1/styles.css"}}' id="mwCfY"/><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./International_Standard_Book_Number" title="International Standard Book Number" id="mwCfc">ISBN</a><span typeof="mw:Entity" id="mwCfg"> </span><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Special:BookSources/978-0-7914-3150-4" title="Special:BookSources/978-0-7914-3150-4" id="mwCfk">978-0-7914-3150-4</a>.</cite></td></tr>
